{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524771"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:08:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:08:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14028"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583900"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:31:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:31:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14028"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14028"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.01,0.43,0.47,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6677"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105643"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6677"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2024-08-03T17:37:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T15:56:46+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-08-03T18:13:46+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-24 10:44:30"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14028"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16151"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88089"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2207"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5788"},{"type":"tags","id":"12909"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38586"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88089"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105643"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with dyspnoea and is admitted to hospital. She has a medical history of end-stage renal disease, hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and asthma. Her regular medications include insulin, amlodipine, and a fluticasone/salmeterol inhaler.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe duty intern is asked to review her as she has developed progressive confusion over the past few hours. Her medication chart shows she has received an extra dose of fast-acting insulin two hours ago with dinner, as well as several doses of nebulised salbutamol and 20 mg of oral morphine for dyspnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a reduced level of consciousness. Her vital signs are: pulse rate 58/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 8/min, SpO2 92% on room air, temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her pupils are sluggish and constricted. Cardiovascular examination reveals normal heart sounds with no murmurs. Respiratory examination shows crackles to midzone bilaterally. There is peripheral oedema to the mid-shin bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 680 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum urea: 32 mmol/L (3.0-8.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum calcium: 2.6 mmol/L (2.1-2.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood glucose: 3.8 mmol/L (3.9-7.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 11 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s confusion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypercalcaemia","Sepsis","Uraemic encephalopathy","Opioid toxicity","Hypoglycaemia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely cause of this patient\u0027s symptoms is \u003Cstrong\u003Eopioid toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient has received a significant dose of morphine (20 mg) in the context of end-stage renal disease. In renal impairment, the active metabolites of morphine (particularly morphine-6-glucuronide) can accumulate, leading to toxicity even with standard doses. The clinical presentation is classic for opioid toxicity: reduced level of consciousness, respiratory depression (respiratory rate 8/min), and constricted, sluggish pupils.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUraemic encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause altered mental status in patients with severe renal failure. However, the acute onset following morphine administration, along with the respiratory depression and miotic pupils, makes opioid toxicity more likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESepsis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause altered mental status, and the patient does have a slightly elevated white cell count. However, sepsis typically presents with fever, tachycardia, and tachypnoea, which are not present in this case. The patient\u0027s temperature is normal, and she is bradypnoeic rather than tachypnoeic. The respiratory depression and miotic pupils are more consistent with opioid toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in end-stage renal disease and cause confusion, but would not explain the respiratory depression or miotic pupils. While the patient\u0027s calcium level is slightly elevated, it is not high enough to account for her severe symptoms. Hypercalcaemia also typically develops more gradually.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypoglycaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause altered mental status and confusion, especially in diabetic patients. However, the patient\u0027s blood glucose level of 3.8 mmol/L is only slightly below the normal range and is unlikely to cause such severe symptoms. Moreover, hypoglycaemia would not explain the respiratory depression or miotic pupils.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to managing this patient is recognising the opioid toxicity, discontinuing the morphine, and considering the use of naloxone if the respiratory depression is severe. In patients with renal impairment, opioids should be used very cautiously, with reduced doses and careful monitoring for signs of toxicity. Alternative strategies for managing dyspnoea in end-stage renal disease, such as non-pharmacological methods or carefully titrated doses of less renally cleared opioids, should be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Opioid toxicity can occur in patients with renal impairment due to accumulation of active metabolites.","Signs of opioid toxicity include respiratory depression, pinpoint pupils, and altered mental status.","Patients with end-stage renal disease require careful dose adjustment of opioids to prevent toxicity"],"references":["Owsiany MT, Hawley CE, Triantafylidis LK, Paik JM. Opioid Management in Older Adults with Chronic Kidney Disease: A Review. Am J Med. 2019;132(12):1386-1393. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6917891/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88089"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14028"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88089"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-11T10:53:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-11T10:53:11+09:30","number":11,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6677"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105643"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://a